1. ADF Test (25% of the HW3 grade)

a) Using a maximum of 12 lags, estimate models of the form \(\Delta s_t = \alpha_0 + \gamma s_{t-1} + \Sigma\beta_i\Delta s_{t-i}\). Use the AIC, BIC, and general-to-specific (GTS) methods to select an appropriate lag length.

First, import quarterly.xls data set and create spread variable by subtracting r5 from Tbill:

df <- read_excel("quarterly.xls")
df <- df %>% mutate(DATE = yearquarter(DATE))
df_tsb <- df %>% as_tsibble(index = DATE)
df_model <- df_tsb %>% filter_index("1961 Q4" ~ "2012 Q4")
df_model <- df_model %>% mutate(spread = r5-Tbill)
df_model <- df_model %>%
  mutate(spread_diff = difference(spread))

Second, estimate 12 ADF models

max_lag <- 12 # setup maximum number of lags
adf_list <- list() # empty list for models
aic_list <- list() # list for AIC values
bic_list <- list() # list for BIC values
for (i in 1:max_lag) {
  adf_list[[i]] <- ur.df2(df_model$spread, lags = i, type = "drift")
  aic_list[[i]] <- adf_list[[i]]$aic
  bic_list[[i]] <- adf_list[[i]]$bic
}

Select models with minimum AIC/BIC

which.min(aic_list)
[1] 9
which.min(bic_list)
[1] 3

Select a lag length using GTS method

e) How is it possible that the individual rates act as I(1) processes whereas the spread acts as a stitionary process?

The individual rates are cointegrated -> linear combination of I(1) processes is an I(0) process.

2. Forecast Evaluation (25% of the HW3 grade)

Create train and test sets

df_train <- df_model[1:(nrow(df_model)-50),]
df_test <- df_model[(nrow(df_model)-49):nrow(df_model),]
h_len <- nrow(df_test) # size of a holdback period

Estimate AR(7) and ARMA[2,(1,7)] models on a train data

# estimate models and generate one-step-ahead forecast
pred_ar7 <- numeric(h_len)
pred_ar217 <- numeric(h_len)

for (i in 1:h_len){
  ar7 <- arima(df_model$spread[1:(155+i-1)], order = c(7,0,0))
  arma217 <- arima(df_model$spread[1:(155+i-1)], order = c(2, 0, 7), 
                      fixed = c(NA,NA, NA,0,0,0,0,0, NA, NA))
  
  pred_ar7[i] <- predict(ar7, n.ahead = 1)$pred
  pred_ar217[i] <- predict(arma217, n.ahead = 1)$pred
}

Let \(e_{1t}\) denote the forecast errors from the AR(7) model and \(e_{2t}\) denote the forecast errors from the ARMA[2,(1,7)] model

# create error terms
e1 <- df_test$spread - pred_ar7
e2 <-  df_test$spread - pred_ar217

Conduct the Granger-Newbold Test

x <- e1 + e2
z <- e1 - e2
# calculate a correlation between z and x
r_zx <- cor(z,x)

# calculate Granger-Newbold statistics
gn_stat <- r_zx/(sqrt((1-r_zx^2)/(length(e1)-1)))

Correlation between \(z_i = e_{1t} - e_{2t}\) and \(x_i = e_{1t} + e_{2t}\) is \(r_{zx}\) = 0.231.
Granger-Newbold statistics is 1.67 that is not statistically significant at \(df = 49\).

3. GARCH (50% of the HW3 grade)

Estimate ARMA[2,(1,7)] model on a full data set

# prepare data set
df_full <- df_tsb %>% filter_index("1960 Q3" ~ "2012 Q4")
df_full <- df_full %>% mutate(spread = r5-Tbill)
df_full <- df_full %>%
  mutate(spread_diff = difference(spread))

# estimate model
arma217 <- arima(df_full$spread, order = c(2, 0, 7), fixed = c(NA,NA, NA, 0,0,0,0,0, NA, NA))

# Estimate the McLeodâLi test using a lag length of seven quarters
df_full$resid2 <- arma217$residuals^2

# regress squared residuals on it's 7th lag
model_mll <- dynlm(resid2 ~ L(resid2, 1:7), data = df_full)

Equation for the McLeodâLi test using a lag length of seven quarters:

\[ \hat{\varepsilon}^2_{t} = 0.075 - 0.021\hat{\varepsilon}^2_{t-1} + 0.13\hat{\varepsilon}^2_{t-2} + 0.09\hat{\varepsilon}^2_{t-3} + 0.256\hat{\varepsilon}^2_{t-4} - 0.027\hat{\varepsilon}^2_{t-5} - 0.091\hat{\varepsilon}^2_{t-6} + 0.304\hat{\varepsilon}^2_{t-7} \]

Conduct LM-Test for an ARCH effect

# create a function to calculate TR^2 and chi-squared at given level
arch_test <- function(model, signif_list, data) {
  len <- nrow(data)
  len_chi <- length(signif_list)
  q <- length(coef(model)) - 1
  r2 <- summary(model)$r.squared
  TR2 <- (len-q)*r2
  
  chi_list <- numeric(len_chi)
  for (i in 1:len_chi) {
    chi_list[i] <- qchisq(1 - signif_list[i], q)
  }
  result <- as.data.frame(c(TR2, chi_list))
  rownames(result) <- c('TR^2', paste0('Chi-squared at ', signif_list*100, '%'))
  colnames(result) <- c('Values')
  result
}

# calculate statistics for residuals of ARMA[2,(1,7)] model
kable(arch_test(model_mll, c(0.05, 0.01), df_full))

Depict an estimated model (note the R doesnât estimate a real intercept for the mean model):

\[ s_{t} = 1.165 + 0.453s_{t-1} + 0.356s_{t-2} + \varepsilon_{t} + 0.725\varepsilon_{t-1} -0.129\varepsilon_{t-7} \]

\[ h_{t} = 0.0116 + 0.193\varepsilon_{t-1}^2 + 0.766h_{t-1} \]

Check autocorrelations for standartized residuals:

# create a function to build acf on standartized residuals
acf_garch <- function(model, max_lag, squared) {
  ifelse(squared == TRUE, assign('resid', model@fit$z^2), assign('resid', model@fit$z))
  acf <- acf(resid, plot = FALSE, lag.max = max_lag)
  acf[1:max_lag]
}

# extract forecasted (fitted) values and boundaries
df_full$fit <- arch3_fit@fit$fitted.values
df_full$high <- df_full$fit + sqrt(var(df_full$fit) * 1.96)
df_full$low <- df_full$fit - sqrt(var(df_full$fit) * 1.96)

df_full %>% ggplot(aes(y = fit, x = DATE)) +
  geom_line() +
  geom_line(aes(y = high, x = DATE), color = "grey", linetype = "dashed") +
  geom_line(aes(y = low, x = DATE), color = "grey", linetype = "dashed") +
  theme_minimal() +
  labs(title = "One-step ahead forecast with 95% confidence interval",
       x = "Quarter",
       y = NULL) +
